==English==

===Etymology===
* First attested in the 1540's.
{{etyl|la}} {{term|acclamatio|acclāmātiō|calling, exclamation, shout of approval|lang=la}}, from {{term|acclamo||shout approvaal or disapproval of, shout out at|lang=la}}, from {{term|ad||toward|lang=la}} + {{term|clamo||cry out|lang=la}}
* Compare French {{term|acclamation|lang=fr}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|US}} {{IPA|/æk.lə.ˈmeɪ.ʃən/}}
* {{rhymes|eɪʃən}}
* {{homophones|acclimation}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# A [[shout]] of [[approbation]], favor, or assent; eager expression of [[approval]]; loud [[applause]].
#: ''On such a day, a holiday having been voted by '''acclamation''', an ordinary walk would not satisfy the children.'' -[[w:Robert Southey|Robert Southey]].
# The process of electing a person to a post in the absence of other nominees.
# {{context|art}} A representation, in [[sculpture]] or on [[medals]], of people expressing joy.
#: '''''Acclamation''' medals are those on which laudatory '''acclamations''' are recorded.'' - [[w:James Elmes|James Elmes]]
# {{context|Canada|political}} Without opposition in an election.
#: ''With no one running against her, she won by '''acclamation'''''.
# {{context|political}} An [[oral]] [[vote]] taken without formal [[ballot]] and with much fanfare; typically an overwhelmingly affirmative vote.

